    <link href="https://lists.linuxfoundation.org/pipermail/bitcoin-dev/2022-July/020663.html" rel="alternate"/>
    <summary>Bitcoin developers have proposed various solutions to improve the functionality and efficiency of transactions using Taproot scripts. One proposal involves updating a UTXO by changing the taproot tree using a new opcode called "TAPLEAF_UPDATE_VERIFY." However, there are concerns about the x-only issue, and potential solutions such as additive tweaking are suggested. The conversation also explores the use of opcodes to achieve specific capabilities for off-chain contract transactions, including the IN_OUT_AMOUNT opcode which allows users to specify authorized ranges for hot wallet withdrawals. The email thread delves into the details of TLUV, a proposed modification to the Revault protocol that enables policies on the Spend transaction for more flexibility but creates implementation complexities.The conversation also discusses the use of recursive covenants for pooled transactions, which allow multiple participants to operate a pool with efficient and private transfers. However, limitations such as the need for all participants to be online to sign via the key path are noted. Additionally, Anthony Towns proposes solutions to issues regarding IN_OUT_AMOUNT and updating the internal pubkey in Taproot. There is also discussion about the safety of the control byte in Taproot due to issues such as indicating the parity of X and the number of steps in the merkle path that are dropped. The TLUV script is used to control how spending scripts can change between the input and output sPK. Furthermore, the bitcoin-dev mailing list discusses the use of recursive covenants for funding joint ventures and the idea behind an automated market maker which involves setting up a script that links the change in value to the BTC utxo and the change in value to the USDT utxo.Overall, the email exchange provides a detailed discussion of the proposed changes to the Taproot protocol and their potential applications, as well as the challenges and proposed solutions in designing secure and efficient transactions. The participants are excited about the progress in the covenant space over the past few years, seeing it as the missing component to allow the creation of more decentralized self-custodial applications built on top of Bitcoin. The conversation revolves around various ways to optimize Taproot's smart contract capabilities while maintaining security and reliability.</summary>
